I want to help young people. I want to work for the Division of Family and Children Services. I want to help young people who are hurt or not taken care of. I want to help families who have problems.  

I am a good worker. I am kind to people. I do the right thing. I want to help people get along. I want to learn more about my job so I can be good at it.

I want to help people. I did not know how to help when I was in school. Some people run from problems. Some people use bad ways to deal with problems. I saw bad things. I went to college to learn about people. 

I finished college in 2009. I helped a young man who was hurt by his parents.  I told the police about my worry. The police asked me to talk to the parents.

I want to help children who have family problems.

I want to help people who are treated bad. Our world says that every person is important. But we often want everyone to be the same. I am different. I do not want to be like everyone else.

In school, I showed that I care about people. I did not like unfair things.

This paper looks at two ways to see insomnia. One way is the biological model. This model looks at genes and health. The other way is the sociocultural model. This model looks at how people live and how this affects sleep. 

Sleep problems can come from many things. Some are main sleep problems. Some are linked to other mental health problems. Some are linked to being sick or taking medicine.

Main sleep problems include trouble falling asleep or staying asleep. They also include sleeping too much. There are also sleep problems that cause strange things to happen while sleeping.

This paper looks at insomnia. It also looks at main sleep problems. It uses the biological and sociocultural models to explain insomnia.

The biological model looks at how genes and the body work together to make us sleep. Some brain cells make a chemical called orexin. Orexin helps us wake up and stay awake.

One study looked at mice. The study found that orexin cells have a special part called a GABAB receptor. This part helps control sleep. When the receptor is turned on, mice sleep more. When it is turned off, mice are less anxious and sleep more.

This study shows that genes and the body can affect sleep. If someone has a problem with the GABAB receptor, they may have trouble sleeping.

The sociocultural model looks at how our lives affect our sleep. For example, stress can make it hard to sleep.

This paper will look at how these models explain insomnia. It will also look at the good and bad parts of these models.

This paper looks at three parts of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). First, we look at what CAPD is. Next, we talk about how doctors find CAPD. We look at signs doctors use to find the problem. Last, we talk about how teachers can help students with CAPD in school.

CAPD, or Auditory Processing Disorder (APD), is a problem with how the brain uses sound. The brain has trouble understanding sound. People with CAPD can hear sounds, but they have trouble understanding them. They may have trouble hearing words in a noisy place.

We first learned about CAPD in the 1950s. Doctors called it “auditory imperception.” They found it in children who had trouble talking. Doctors started making tests for CAPD in the 1960s. A big meeting in 1977 helped doctors learn more about CAPD.

CAPD can look different in different people. Some people have trouble hearing sounds in space. Some have trouble telling sounds apart. Some have trouble hearing patterns in sound. Some have trouble understanding changes in voices. Some have trouble remembering sounds. 

Doctors use tests to find CAPD. They watch how people listen to sounds. They use tests to see how well people understand sounds. There is no one test for CAPD. Doctors do not know why people get CAPD.

The play Twelfth Night show us that disguises can help people hide. But, people must stop hiding. They must be true to themself. If not, they may lose who they are.

It is hard to stop hiding. Some people will be mad. They may feel hurt. 

Twelfth Night talks about men and women hiding. This is a big problem. Why do people hide? Why do they want to be someone else?

Viola hides. She is a woman, but she acts like a man. She does this to be safe. She says: "I will take you to a man in this town. He will help me. He will keep me safe."

Viola hides well. But she is alone. She is not with other women.

Olivia thinks Viola is a man. She likes Viola. She says: "Stay, my husband. Do not go."

Viola also likes Orsino. But Orsino likes Viola too. He says: "You have said you will not love a woman like me."


Twelfth Night shows us that hiding can help people feel things. Olivia and Orsino like Viola/Cesario. They may like men or women.

Olivia likes Viola as a man. But she likes Sebastian too. She changes her mind quickly. She sees Viola as a sister, not a lover. She says: "You are my sister."

German rule was very hard on some people. This is true for the Ovaherero and Nama people in German South West Africa. But German rule was not the same in all places. German rule was different in different places. This is true for how they taught people too. When the British took over German East Africa in 1919, many Africans could read and write. This was because the Germans taught them. The Germans also did good work in Kamerun and other places. 
But South West Africa was different. The German government did not teach many Africans. The job of teaching Africans was left to churches. The churches did not get much help from the government. The government did help teach Europeans. They built schools for them. The government also help the churches teach Europeans. This had a big effect on South West Africa even after the Germans left. Other German places had many African people who could read and write. But in South West Africa, most people could not read or write. There are many reasons for this. This paper will look at these reasons. It will also look at how people who lived in South West Africa felt about African people.

There are many books about teaching in German places. Many of these books are in German. They were written when the Germans ruled these places. These books talk about how teaching worked in different places. Later books in English talk about teaching in all the German places. They also talk about special parts of teaching. These books show that teaching was different in each place. One book talks about teaching in South West Africa and East Africa. The book says that the many people who came to live in South West Africa made teaching different there.

South West Africa was not as hot as some other places Germany ruled. But much of the land was desert. Many Europeans came to live in South West Africa. In 1913, almost 15,000 Europeans lived there. This was more than any other German place except East Africa.

Popular music has many kinds. It is hard to name them all. Many kinds have small kinds inside them. Rock, rap, country, jazz, and folk are some examples. Heavy metal rock is one kind that is very big now. 

Heavy metal is good at showing many feelings. These feelings are often sad or dark. People like to make new kinds of heavy metal. They make small kinds and then even smaller kinds. There are many kinds of heavy metal now. It is hard to say what heavy metal is.

Heavy metal is like a big group of people. It started a long time ago. Heavy metal is loud. It has strong beats. It is also very good. People in metal bands know how to play music well. 

Heavy metal is also linked to drugs. In the 1970s, people used a lot of drugs. This made music sound strange. Heavy metal had dark feelings. This was new to music.  

Heavy metal also took ideas from old music. Old music from the Romantic time had dark feelings too. 

One song that is like heavy metal is "Helter Skelter" by The Beatles. This song has sad feelings. Some people think it is one of the first heavy metal songs. The Beatles made this song to show they could be as loud as the Rolling Stones.

Many years ago, before the Surrealist artists made dream art, Henri Rousseau made his own dreams. He made art about dreams. The painting The Dream is from 1910. It shows a woman in a dream. The woman sees good things. Rousseau made this painting to show his own dreams. He wanted people to like his art.

Rousseau wanted other artists to like his art. He wanted people who loved art to like it too.  He had a hard time. He wanted to make art like other artists. He also wanted to make art that was different. 

To understand Rousseau, we need to know his life. He was born in France in 1844. His father was a worker. Rousseau did not learn to make art. He worked for the government. He had a sad life. His wife died. He had many babies who died. He made art to feel better. 

Rousseau loved art. He wanted to be part of the art world. He was older than many art students. He did not know much about art. He worked hard and made art. He did not get famous until later. He wanted to make art that was easy to like. He wanted people to say his art was good.

Many good people think that good things and good looks are close. They think truth and beauty are close too. I think there is a good reason for this. John Keats said, “Beauty is truth, truth beauty. That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know.” We learn much in life. We learn from school and from life. But we like good things and good looks without learning. Keats is right. Good things and good looks are like tries to say what is right. We study good things and good looks to say why one work is good or why one act is good. We do not learn rules to make good things or good acts.

But we can not say all about what is good or what is good looking. We can talk about a painting like Da Vinci's Mona Lisa. We can talk about color and shape. But this does not say why it is good art. When we like art or a book, we say, “There is something about it.” This is hard to say. I think art and good things can not be fully said. Flannery O'Connor said, "A story is a way to say something that can not be said any other way. You tell a story because words are not enough.” No matter how much we say about a story, there is more.

I think good things and art are close because we feel them deep inside. They make us feel things we can not fully explain. This is true for stories even more. Stories have good things in them. This is why stories are important to us.

Germany is a strong country. It has one mix of culture. This culture goes from the mountains in München to the city of Kiel by the sea. You can feel this same culture in Köln on the Rhine River. It goes to Dresden, a city in Saxony on the Elbe River. Germany is a new country. It came from many tribes.

Germania is the old name for Germany. Historians talk about the name a lot. Tacitus said the name came from a tribe called the Tungrians. They were called Germans before they crossed the Rhine River to fight the Gauls. Julius Caesar first used the word "Germanus." He used it in his book about the Gallic Wars. He used it to talk about the people he did not beat in his wars. Some people think "Germanus" came from the Gauls. Caesar wrote about the Germans in his book. He said they fought the Gauls all the time. 

Tacitus wrote a book about the Germans. He said they were from the land and had not mixed with other people. He said no one would go to Germany. He said it was a hard place to live. 

The Romans fought the Germans. They wanted things from Germany. The Romans also fought wars in Germany. But they did not stay there.

The Germans lived near the Roman Empire. They traded with the Romans. They also worked in the Roman army.

I look down. I see the thing in front of me. I think about it. But I am not sad or happy. I just look.

A friend told me to read a book about art. It is called "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain." I want to learn to draw. This book tells how the brain sees lines.  

The book says to draw a box around a picture. This helps to see the big things. Not the small things.

I look at the thing. I cannot see the box. It is too much. I am happy.

Artists paint in many ways. Picasso used blue. Monet used green. I want to make my art. I will call it "Work in Brown."

I take a tool. I want to make art. The water goes down. The thing does not go down.  

I get a mop. I wear a tie. I am not happy.

I look at the thing. It is bad. I flush it again. I look at it again.

I take the toilet paper. I make a glove. I get it wet. I put it in the thing.

I stand up. I bend down. I put my hand in the water.

Young people die in car crashes. Many things make this a big problem. The National Institutes of Health say teen brains are not ready to drive. Teens also have little driving practice. This causes many crashes. Teens drive faster. They also drive off the road more.  Teens are more likely to crash when friends are in the car. 

Some states have rules to help teen drivers. They give teens special driver's permits. These permits limit driving time and the number of young friends in the car. 

But these rules are not enough. The big problem is that young drivers are not ready for the dangers of driving. Doctor Marvin Zuckerman says 18 is too young to drive. He says young people want to take risks. This is why it is good to wait to drive.

If we keep giving driver's licenses to young teens, more people will die in crashes. Many more teenagers will be able to drive soon. We need to make new rules to keep teens safe.

Schools can teach teens about driving. But no one under 18 should drive a car. Teens can get a special permit to practice. They must also practice with an adult.  Many states have rules about how much practice is needed. We should have the same rules in all states.

This is not a new idea.

I look at old films by Thomas Edison. I see fifteen trick films. These films are from 1895 to 1901. Trick films use special cutting to show tricks.

I study how the films look. I look for new things in later films. Most trick films are short. They use one camera set up. The camera does not move.

The films are like a stage play. The actors move left and right. They do not move closer or farther from the camera.

For example, look at "Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel" (1900). The actors move side to side.

The camera does not follow them.

Trick films use long shots. They do not use close-ups.

Trick films are very short. They are like short shows. They show magic tricks.

Each trick film is one idea. Each idea is one film. For example, "The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots" is one film. But it uses many short films to make the tricks.

John Taylor liked the new government of the United States. He wanted it to be good. Taylor was a farmer. He worked hard in the fields. He also worked in the government for a short time.  He was strong and said what he thought. He liked the idea of people owning their own land. He thought this was the best way to live. 

Taylor thought the United States had a good chance to make a good government. There was no old way to stop them. This meant they could make a government that worked for the people. He believed people had rights that should be protected. He said if one right was lost, all rights would be lost.

Taylor thought a good government needed to help people. He thought people are good and bad. He said, "The government is made by people. It will have good and bad parts." He said a good government protects people's land, helps farmers, and does not let rich people have too much power.

Taylor wanted the government to follow the rules in the Constitution. He did not want the government to be too big or powerful. He said, "A big government can be bad." He also said that people should read the Constitution and think about what the writers really meant. He liked the Declaration of Independence. He thought it said that the states were separate and strong.

Figure 17 shows a big drop in commuter logs in the third month. This was sad. We do not know why this happened. Winter came to the New England campus. Fewer people ride bikes or walk to school. This may be a reason for the drop. December is the end of the fall school time. Students are very busy with school work. They may not fill out the logs. December is also a busy time for holidays. Students and teachers have a long break. They do not need to come to school. Classes start again in late January. This may be a reason for the low number of logs then. But we do not know why there were so few logs in February.

Maybe projects start with lots of energy. This energy can go down over time. 

We made a special event called Carpool Challenge Week in March. We tried to make people more interested. More people filled out logs in March. 

One problem is keeping people interested. Holidays and school breaks make this harder.

Another problem is that people like to drive cars. It is easy and free. We gave away prizes to encourage people to use other ways to get to school. We gave gift cards. It would be good to give bigger prizes. Maybe a bike, a new car, or an electric car. This might help more people join the project.

The prizes did not change during the project. Maybe we should have given bigger prizes later in the project. The gift cards were good at the start. But maybe people would have been more interested if we had said we would give away bikes in December, and a new car in January.

An ETF is like a basket of things you can buy. It goes up and down like a single thing. ETFs are good for many things. They are like a group of things but easy to buy and sell. ETFs are cheaper than some other baskets. 

ETFs have good things. You can buy small parts of them. But you pay a small cost each time you buy or sell.  There are many different kinds of ETFs.

This paper looks at an ETF called IHF. We look at the ten things inside IHF. We want to know if IHF is good. We want to know if it is better to buy IHF or buy each of the ten things inside.

We look at how much money is in each thing. We use this to see how much each thing makes money. We use this to see how much risk each thing has.

We find that the ten things make more money than IHF. But IHF has more risk. We want to know if this is important.

To know this, we look at how much each thing changes in price. We see if IHF is different from the ten things.

Poe likes the poem "Dream-Land". In the poem, Poe uses the word "Thulé". This word is from Virgil. Virgil used it for an island. The Greeks thought it was far away. Poe liked German writers. One writer was Goethe.  A book says Poe like Goethe's poem "Faust". The book says Poe copied "Faust". "Faust" is a long poem. It has two parts. The second part has a short poem called "The King of Thulé".  This poem is sad. The king is lonely. His wife is dead. He drinks too much. He is sad. He goes to a cliff. He throws a cup in the sea. He closes his eyes and dies. The king in "Dream-Land" is sad too. He is like the king in "The King of Thulé". Poe used the word "Thulé" in other poems too. Poe used it in "The Pit and the Pendulum". Poe used it twice in "Dream-Land". "Dream-Land" is like "The King of Thulé". The speaker in "Dream-Land" is sad. He is in a dark place. He sees his dead friends. He sees a dark world. These things are in "The King of Thulé" too. Goethe was a famous writer. Poe liked him. Poe liked Tennyson too. Tennyson liked Goethe.  Poe read many of Goethe's works.

A person was hurt in a store in California. They fell on applesauce. Can they get more money? The money is called ‘punitive damages.’  They say the store manager was bad. He knew about the spill twice. He did not clean it up. He was eating dinner. A judge will not throw out the case right away.

To get more money, the hurt person must show the manager did something bad on purpose. The manager knew it was bad. He did not care.  The hurt person can say the manager knew this was bad. Other people fell before. The manager did not clean up. The hurt person can also say the manager was mean. Six people fell before. He did not make the store safe.

On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 pm, an worker told the manager about the applesauce. The manager was eating. He said he did not have time. At 5:15 pm, another worker told the manager. He said the same thing. At 5:30 pm, the hurt person fell. She was hurt badly. Five other people fell that year.

The hurt person is suing the store. She wants money for her hurt and more money for the store's bad actions.

In California, a person can get more money if a store does something very bad. The store manager must be mean. He must want to hurt people.  Or he did not care if people got hurt.

Four years ago, I took a class about Islam. We talked about if Islam is a bad religion. This is still a big question today. After nine eleven, the news showed Islam in bad ways. Now, the news shows Islam in good ways. We could not have had a president named Barack Obama in 2001. He is Muslim.

The story of Muhammad is interesting. I thought Muhammad was strong. He took over groups and made them follow Islam. But the story says he was kind. People liked him and joined Islam.

Muhammad's story is like Jesus' story. For example, Muhammad made food for many people. This makes Muhammad seem like a good man. But this makes Jesus' miracles less important. It is not good to copy Jesus.

There are many stories about people joining Islam. But some stories are not true. They are from people who heard from other people. This makes the stories seem fake.

I do not like how the story makes Muhammad seem good. History shows he was not kind. I wonder if Muslims know the truth about Muhammad.

Jesus teach good things.  His ideas help people.  But after Jesus die, people change his ideas.  Today, people want new things.  They want to think new thoughts.  Some people like old ways.  But they are not many.

People want to know what Jesus really teach.  They want to find the old ways. This will take time.  Many years may pass.  But people will go back to Jesus' ideas.  

People will make Christianity like it was in Jesus' time.  They will go back to the simple ways.  Lots of people will join this way. They will put away old ideas.  They will go back to the start.

This will be good.  People will be more alike.   This has happened before.  The Roman Empire was once bad to Christians.  But then the empire became Christian.  

People will find Jesus' words in new ways.  They will see that his words are like stories. 

Before Jesus, there was Judaism.  Jewish people believed in one God.  They read old books.  

Jewish people had many thoughts.   They were Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and many others.

The Jungle shows that humans are greedy. They only want good things for them. They do not care about others. The book shows this with the factory owners. They want big factories. They do not care if people get hurt. 

The book says, "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world". This shows the bad things the smoke does. The owners do not care. They do not care about the people or animals.

The owners do not care about the workers. They want to save money. They make the workers work long hours. They fire workers without help.

There were no good laws to help the workers. The owners could do bad things. The workers had to work in bad places. The book says the workers were like slaves. They had no way to escape.

Many writers want their readers to feel a way about things. They use many ways to do this. Some ways are more good than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald is a writer. He uses many ways to make readers feel things in his book *The Great Gatsby.* 

Fitzgerald sometimes puts words together that do not go well. This makes things seem special. He also uses things to show feelings. He uses colors in this way.

Fitzgerald uses gold, green, white, gray, and red, pink to show feelings. He uses white and gray in *The Great Gatsby* to show things are the same. White is better, more rich. Gray is old and not new.

Fitzgerald shows this at the start of the book. Daisy and Jordan wear white a lot. Nick wears white to Gatsby’s party. Tom wears white when he meets Myrtle. Everyone wears white! The only time people do not wear white is when Nick is at Gatsby’s party. The party is full of bright colors.

Fitzgerald shows white and gray in many things. Nick goes to work in a white place. Names at Gatsby’s party are gray on Nick’s list. Catherine’s home is like a white cake. Fitzgerald calls common things white or gray. Jordan and Daisy had a white girlhood.

Fitzgerald uses white and gray to show things are not important. He does this with Daisy. He describes Daisy in white. She is in a white car. Readers see Daisy as less important. She is like something Gatsby wants. Fitzgerald uses white and gray around Daisy more to show this.

San Diego area has good farms. The weather is good. Many people grow food there. They grow many kinds of food: tomatoes, oranges, lettuce, squash, broccoli, herbs, peaches, lemons, berries, honey, and peppers.  

People like to buy food from farms. They want food made without chemicals. Many farms sell food this way. Many farms also have tours. People can walk on farms and see animals.

Organic farms are good for animals and plants. They use no bad chemicals. But, organic farms cost more to run. People must work hard to grow food without chemicals.

This farm is near the town of Potrero. It is one hundred sixty acres. There are many trees and plants there. Some plants and animals are rare. This farm was used for many years. People lived there and grew food.

I looked at farms like this one. I see how a farmer can use the farm to help animals and make money.

Culture is big in talk deals. Culture is what people do and think. It is not the same for all people. Some say all people from one place are the same. This is not true. It is good to know some things about people from other places. But it is better to know how they think about the deal. When you talk to people from another place, you think of your own place. You see things like your own place.

To know people, you can look at their history. You can see what they believe. Do not judge people. Just know them. Work with them. If you are not strong in the deal, be nice. If you go to their place, be polite.

Culture is not just about countries. Companies have their own ways. Some companies work long hours. Some work less. You can see this in how people dress and talk.

America is big. Companies are different. Some help poor people. Some do not.

Values are important. They show why people do things. If people care about face, they will not be mean. If people like hard work, they will not give up easily.

Before you talk, learn about people. Learn what is important to them.

The wise man say, "God is real." This word is in the Bible. A man named Anselm use this word to talk about God. Another man, Thomas Aquinas, also talk about God.  Both men want to show that God is real. We will look at both men's ideas. We will say both men are right. Both men talk about the God in the Bible.

Anselm say that we can find God in our minds. He say we know God is real because we can think about God.  We do not need to see God to know he is real. This is like faith.

Aquinas say we can find God with our brains. He say we can see God in the world. He give five reasons why God is real. He say that the world needs God. It is like a puzzle. We can see all the pieces, but one is missing. We know the missing piece is there.

Both men have good ideas. But neither man show us that God is really real.

Buddha was a prince. He was born many years ago. He left the world. He found peace. He taught his ideas. People made a new religion. It is called Buddhism. One part of Buddhism is called Theravada. This part is old. It is two thousand five hundred years old.

Theravada is different now. It is different from when Buddha was alive. People do things now that Buddha did not teach. This is true in Sri Lanka. Monks and people go to a water cut. They do this every year. It is a special act.

Theravada Buddhism has changed. It changed over time. This change was from inside and outside. Some things helped. Some things hurt.

We will talk about these changes. We will use special words.

Inside means from people in Buddhism. Outside means from people not in Buddhism.

Hostile means bad. It hurts Buddhism. Benign means not bad. It does not help or hurt Buddhism.

First, we learn about Buddhism. We learn about its ideas.

Buddhists find peace in three things: Buddha, Dhamma, and Sangha.

Dhamma is the book of Buddha’s ideas. It has three parts:

Sutta Pitaka has Buddha’s talks.

Vinaya Pitaka has rules for monks.

Abhidhamma Pitaka has ideas about how things work.

These ideas say that life has much pain. We want things. We hate. We are confused. To stop this, we must stop wanting. We must stop hating. We must stop being confused.  This ends the cycle of life and death.

The Vinaya Pitaka has rules for life. People have five rules. Monks have many more rules.

The most important idea is the Four Noble Truths.

First: Life has pain.

Second: We want things. This makes pain.

Third: We can stop pain.

The United States and Mexico had a big problem for many years. This problem lasted for fifty-seven years. It began in 1836 and ended in 1893. [Diehl and Goerts 2000 p. 145]. The biggest problem was the Mexican-American War. This war was from 1846 to 1848. The United States fought Mexico and won. The United States took Texas and the Southwest. There were other problems between the two countries. They stopped fighting just before World War I.

The United States and Mexico had problems because of religion, culture, and money. [Schmitt 1974 p. 30-31].  Many countries have problems with their neighbors. Countries near each other often have different wants. This can make them fight. The United States and Mexico are like other countries with problems. David M. Pletcher said, "Only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting American diplomatic problems" [Pletcher 1977 p. 41]. Both countries are close to the United States and have had problems. Other countries in Latin America have good relations with the United States.

Religion was a big problem for the United States and Mexico.  Sally Frahm said, "If in the twentieth century Americans were opposed to fascism and communism, in the eighteenth and nineteenth they were opposed to Catholicism and monarchy" [Frahm 2001 p.86]. The United States and the Soviet Union fought during the Cold War. This was because they had different ideas and wanted different things. The United States and Mexico fought because of religion. People in England and Spain did not like each other. This made it hard for the United States and Mexico to get along.

Diehl and Goerts said there were seventeen problems between the United States and Mexico. [Diehl and Goerts 2000]. Most of the problems were about land. Bandits from the United States hurt people in Mexico. This was a big problem. Both countries sent soldiers to the border to stop it. [Schmitt 1974 p. 97].

Mexico needed the United States. This made the rivalry go away. [Schmitt 1974 p. 109].

Fifteen years ago, I got very sick. The illness was new to me. I was a nurse. I worked as a nurse because I wanted to be safe. I did not have a safe home when I was a child. People told me, "You can always find work. People always get sick." So, I chose nursing. 

But then I got sick. I am 46. I am single. I have no money. I can not work. I am still sick. I live on Social Security. I have nothing. Each day is hard. I am not safe. I have no good feeling about myself.  

I am lucky. My family and friends help me. I am strong. But I know I need them. Real bad things happen. We need help.

We need to help each other. We need to trust each other. We need to ask for help. We need to work together. 

I agree that we need to be careful. We need to plan. But we need to help each other.

People say that America was built on strong people. But it was not just strong people. It was kindness. It was respect. It was sharing.

Be ready. Have a plan. But also, know your neighbors.

Why do things in nature change over time? Are there rules that show how these changes happen?  A long time ago, a man named D’Arcy Thompson said it was hard to use math to show even the simplest life forms. This is still true today.  Recently, people have used math to study how shells form. We studied a group of shells called Prunum. We wanted to see if math could help us understand how shells change over time.

We took pictures of Prunum shells. We used math to study the shapes of these shells. We used a computer program to make new shell shapes. We wanted to see what shapes were possible. We are also studying how Prunum shells change in the real world. This will help us understand how shells change over time.

A shell is like a tube that spins.  It spins in a circle.  Each turn is called a whorl. The whorls are like steps on a spiral. The center of the spiral is called the columella.  The whorls grow at different speeds. The line between each whorl is called a suture.

The last whorl is the biggest. All the whorls except the last one are the spire. The tip of the spire is the apex. The other end is the base. The animal lives inside the shell. It comes out through an opening called the aperture.

We can look at shells in different ways. We can look at the top, the bottom, the opening, and the other side. The usual way to look at a shell is with the opening facing us.

To count the whorls, we look at the shell from the top. We find the first suture. We draw a line across the shell. We count the whorls from this line.

We can think of a shell as a series of openings. The openings move through space and time as the animal builds its shell. We can use math to show how the openings move.

We can use math to change how the shell grows.

Indonesia is a country in Asia.  Indonesia has made some good changes in health.  But, Indonesia still has problems with babies and new mothers.  Many babies and new mothers die each year. 

Indonesia wants to help many people.  Indonesia wants to help people get clean water and good bathrooms.  Indonesia wants to help make babies and mothers healthy.

Indonesia has more helper people at births now.  But, not all helpers are doctors.  Some helpers are not good for sick babies.  Many babies die from bleeding after birth.

Indonesia has fewer sick babies now.  But, not all sick babies see a doctor.  

Few babies have surgery.  Few babies in the country have surgery.  People in cities have more surgery than people in the country.  This is a problem.

Poor people have less help with health.  They need more help.

Indonesia must decide how to help people.  One way is to help one group of people, like babies.  Another way is to help all people.  

Helping one group is easy.  But, it can hurt other groups.   It can be hard to help everyone, but it is better in the long run.

Victorian books are known for many details. They often show the rich people of that time.  Two famous books from that time are different. They are *Oliver Twist* and *Wuthering Heights*.  These books have mystery and strange things in them. This is not like other books from that time. The mystery helps us know more about the characters. We see their feelings and why they do things.

Here is a part from *Oliver Twist*:

“Many new and confusing thoughts came to his mind. He was still walking between Sikes and Crackit. They were angry and talking.  He heard their words in his ears. When he paid attention to himself, he was talking to them too. Suddenly, he heard gunshots. Loud cries and shouts filled the air. Lights flashed before his eyes. It was loud and noisy. Someone was taking him away quickly. He felt pain all through these things. The pain was bad and hurt him a lot.”


These two books use mystery often. They use dreams or dreamlike states. The dreams are different in each book. In *Oliver Twist*, the strange dreams show us about Oliver. We see his sadness and how he sees the world. When Oliver is shot, he remembers it in a dream. He is trying to find help. The part shows that Oliver had no control over what happened. He was very sick. He sees Sikes and Crackit in his dream. The shooting hurts him very much. He does not feel anything else. He does not even feel the hand that takes him away. He feels sad and afraid.

We wonder who caused Oliver's bad luck. It was not his fault. This shows that Oliver has no control over his life.  He cannot even try to stop bad things from happening. 

Here is a part from *Wuthering Heights*:

“The day passed quickly. It was gone as soon as it came. Night came again. It was a long night, but it felt short. Long in its quiet and short in its passing hours.”

Two years ago, I worked with young students after school. I helped them with school work. I was good at English and reading. A teacher asked me to help a boy named Adrian. He was in third or fourth grade. Adrian had big problems with reading. 

He read some letters good. He read other letters bad. It was strange. Adrian spoke English well. He was from Mexico. 

One day, Adrian's mother came to the school. She only spoke Spanish. I knew a little Spanish. We talked. I understood. Adrian read fine. He did not know the English letters well.

I tell this story about the language problem in schools. It is hard for some students. Even if they speak English well, reading can be hard. What can we do? 

Adrian needed help with English letters and sounds. Other students need more help. There is no one answer. We need many things:

* Dual language programs are good. All students can learn two languages.

* Mainstream immersion helps some students.
* Private tutors can help.
* ESL classes are important.

We need to use many things to help students.

Many people think about big ideas when they grow up. Some go to church. Some go to temple. Some think about these ideas alone. Some people agree with the ideas of their family. Some people do not. We all try to know who we are. We look for good things to help us.

My father liked cardinals. We sat on the porch. It rained hard. We smoked. The rain made the plants sad. My father looked at the rain. He looked far away. He was thin. His hair was not much. He did not look at me. I wanted to talk to him. But I did not. I hugged him. We sat close and looked at the rain.

My father died that year. He was sick. The doctors said he would not live long. He died five days after my birthday. I did not go to see him die. I did not want to. My father did not want me to see him die. I stayed in bed for three days. No one called me.

The Gothic story is old and new. This is what Ian Watt says in his book. Some people say the Gothic story is not good. Other people say it is very good.  The first Gothic story was by Horace Walpole. He wrote "The Castle of Otranto". Walpole took ideas from old stories and new stories. He made a new kind of story. He used old ways of acting and new ways of writing about nature. He called it a "Gothic story".  Gothic stories use old ideas from the Middle Ages. They use old stories, buildings, and ways of life.  

The word "Gothic" was used for many things. People thought it was old and not good. They thought new things were better.  Gothic stories used old ideas and new ways of writing. This is why Gothic stories are still read today.  

One idea that is often in Gothic stories is chivalry. Chivalry is the way knights were trained. Walpole liked chivalry. He liked the idea of knights being brave and good. He thought people were not like knights today. 

Walpole wrote "The Castle of Otranto" when there was trouble in the government. He was worried about the future.  He saw good things in the past. He thought people were better then. He wrote about a knight named Frederic. Frederic is brave and good.

Supply chain work is the way goods move. This starts when a customer buys something. Then, it goes to the parts, to making the good, and finally to the customer. A person named Keith Oliver said the word "supply chain" in 1982. He said it is about planning, doing, and watching how goods move. This is to make sure customers get what they want fast. There are six parts to supply chain work: making, getting parts, keeping parts, place, moving, and info. Managers use these six parts to help customers.

Making is the first part. It is important for all of the other parts. Making plans when, where, and how to make the goods. Managers must know what people want. They look at the market to find out. The market shows what people need. When managers know what people want, they decide what to make and how much. They also decide where to make it. This must be a good place to make the goods and keep customers happy.

After making a plan, managers plan work and keep machines working. Making is very important. If plans are not good, it can cost a lot of time and money. For example, I worked at stores. They have plans for everything. This helps them work well.

The second part of supply chain work is getting parts. This means deciding how to make things and who to work with. A company may make different parts in different places. Each place has different workers and tools. The manager must decide where to make each part. Sometimes, managers give work to other companies. This is to make things go faster and cheaper.

Brothers have a strong bond. This bond is strong and real. It has many feelings: love, pride, meanness, and bad things. Brothers know each other very well. They see themselves in each other. 

When things are bad, the bond shows its true form. This form can be good or bad. The feelings have big costs. To know these feelings, we must deal with the results. When we look in a brother's eyes, we see ourselves. We see our true self. 

Our actions show who we are.  "The Scarlet Ibis" talks about this. Two brothers feel these strong feelings. They go on a trip in a beautiful place. They are sad and proud. The main feeling is pride. From the start, the brother feels bad about Doodle. He wants a brother who can do things: run, jump, climb. He wants to race and play. But Doodle is sick. He cannot be strong. This makes the brother sad. He even thinks about hurting Doodle.

The brain is hard to understand. It good at many things. People use words to talk about the brain. They say the brain is like a tablet, like paper, like a book. Now, people say the brain is like a computer. These words help us think about the brain. But, they not show all that the brain can do.

The brain takes in information. The eyes see light. The ears hear sounds. The brain changes this into signals. The brain use these signals to help us understand the world.

For example, if we see a black box, the brain sees the lines and the color. The brain knows this is a box. The brain also use what we already know to help. We know a box is a thing. We see a black box, so it must be a thing.

The brain is very good at picking out important things. We look at grass. The brain sees all the grass. But we do not think about each blade. We hear our name in a loud room. Our brain picks out our name.

The leader of this world make the people happy by giving them things. The leader make the people spend money. The people do not know they are being tricked.

Culture plays a significant role in any negotiation. Culture can be defined as much by what it is not as what it actually is and what it signifies. Culture is not homogenous, nor is it a specific thing. It is also not singular or uniform. Statements such as “all Russians are stubborn” or “all Japanese are accommodating,” are inherently broad and overly simplistic. While the understanding of a culture’s generalizations are appropriate, it is much more productive to a negotiator to understand the significance of a culture to the matter at hand, and how that culture’s attitude can and will affect the table talks. When one approaches a foreign culture, one experiences it in a way that is relatable to his own culture, and comparisons necessarily arise. 

Attempting to understand a foreign culture or mindset can involve anything from studying its history to realizing its prejudices. Rather than judging or attempting to change a culture, one must simply accept it for what it is, and work within its boundaries, especially within the scope of negotiation, and most especially if one comes to the table with a weaker bargaining position. Likewise, if a negotiator finds himself on “away” territory, a respect for traditions and beliefs can only help in getting over any cultural barriers and move the negotiation forward.

It is important to note that culture does not necessarily limit itself to a national/international dichotomy. Most companies within a given nation establish their own corporate culture. For instance, a corporate culture might emphasize long hours in the office or a more relaxed schedule. Evidence of a corporate culture can be seen in employee dress codes, in communication style (direct v. indirect communication, delegation of duties), and hiring practices. Some companies encourage philanthropy at any level from employees, others restrict it to “company approved” charities or fundraisers. One need only look at the differences in American corporate culture from company to company (and indeed, intra-company diversity exists even from region to region, urban to suburban environments included) to appreciate the diversity of thought that can reside within a particular societal culture. Certain cultures are not nearly as stratified as American culture, and may appear more uniform to an outsider, but a similar exterior is simply a sign to dig deeper. 

Values are even more important to understand, because they provide the why of a culture. If saving face or communal harmony are valued within a culture, it is certain that a negotiator will not publicly shame his company or his superior in order to succeed at the negotiation table. Likewise, a negotiator from a culture which gives greater weight to a hard-driven bargain will not necessarily be driven to settle at the earliest opportunity. Taking these generalities into consideration is important before one gets to the negotiating table. However, a negotiator is well-served to learn something about his opponent on a personal level in order to make the negotiation effective.

“The fool hath said in his heart, ‘There is no God.’” The preceding quotation is seen first in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible, and is found at the beginning of St. Anselm’s argument regarding the existence of God. This belief seems to also be held by the other author whom we will be discussing, Thomas Aquinas. Because each of their arguments is in defense of the same concept, and our challenge is to determine who’s is the better of the two, we must, for sake of brevity, begin with the presumption that they are both correct in their belief in the existence of God, specifically the God of the Bible. To allow for a God-type figure that may not resemble the one in whom our two authors believe would not permit us to appropriately compare their two arguments, as they are essentially in defense of one specific concept of God. That being said, I would suggest that while each of them brings up valid points, neither truly provides a holistic basis for belief in God.
	To illustrate this point, we will first examine the basic argument of St. Anselm. Anselm’s passage reflects a path of gaining understanding through faith, looking within one’s self to find proof of God. He explains that because God exists within our understanding, we cannot effectively conceive his nonexistence. While this concept, when spelled out in his terminology, is a bit tedious and at times unclear, the basic gist of it is that the proof for God lies within one’s own mind. St. Anselm is suggesting to us that we needn’t go beyond the confines of our own soul to find truth about God, but that the existence of this being is found to be true simply by examining that which we inherently know to be true within our own minds. Foreign evidence is presumably unnecessary. This concept of accepting that for which there is not an irrefutable body of empirical evidence is often referred to within Christian texts as faith.
	This idea is very different from that held by St. Thomas Aquinas. Aquinas instead suggests that the existence of God can be proven entirely through reason and empirical evidence, with no need for faith of any kind. Such an idea would be beneficial in evangelism, an important element of Christianity, because it would enable the recruiting of new converts without any dependency upon their willingness to accept something that cannot be proven. They could instead be persuaded by logic alone. St. Thomas elaborates on five different logical arguments supporting the existence of God: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. In each he essentially demonstrates that the proof of God lies in the logical necessity for God. If you are told that that you are missing one puzzle piece, and assemble the rest of the puzzle, logic dictates that you can know of the features and the existence of the missing piece without having to see it.

Many authors use different ways to give their readers a certain feeling or attitude toward
important subjects. Some of these techniques are more effective than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald uses
many of these different techniques in his novel The Great Gatsby. Sometimes, Fitzgerald pairs an
adjective and a noun together that do not usually fit that way to give readers a certain aura around a
subject. Other times, he applies meaning to a symbol, and then uses it for this same purpose.
Fitzgerald uses this last technique with many colors, including gold, green, white/gray and red/pink. In
his novel The Great Gatsby F. Scott Fitzgerald builds up meaning for colors, namely white/gray and
red/pink then later uses that meaning to give readers a certain reminder of a feeling around an
important object.
The meaning Fitzgerald builds up and uses for white/gray is uniformity, with white being a bit
nicer and higher class and gray being more older and faded. Fitzgerald sets up this meaning in the
beginning of the novel with constant uses of both. Daisy and Jordan are constantly “in white” (8)—in
fact, everyone is always wearing white: Nick wears “white flannels” (41) to Gatsby’s party, Tom wears
a “white shirt” (36) when he meets Myrtle, and Catherine is “powdered milky white” (30). In fact, the
only time people are not wearing white is when Nick is getting his impressions of Gatsby’s party: “the
halls... are gaudy with primary colors” (40). Fitzgerald further defines these two colors in coloring
many common, unimportant subjects these colors: as Nick goes to work, he goes “down the white
chasms of lower New York” (56), the names of people at Gatsby’s parties are now “gray names” (61)
on Nick’s timetable, Catherine’s apartment is “one slice in a long white cake of apartment-houses”—
uniformity (28). He also describes plain or common people or places as white or gray: Jordan and
Daisy had a “white girlhood” (19) together, there are “gray cars” and “gray land” (23) in the valley of
ashes, the “Italian child” in the railroad is “gray” (26), and the dog-seller is “a gray old man” (27).
After Fitzgerald adds enough meaning to white/gray, he uses them to signify unimportance or
uniformity to certain subjects. This using colors to show readers something first starts with Daisy.
After a long time without any significant use of either of these colors, Fitzgerald comes out describing
Daisy as “dressed in white” in “a little white roadster”; readers begin to see Daisy as less of a character,
more like just a uniform addition, something that Gatsby wants and longs for (74). Fitzgerald uses
more of this technique around Daisy to give this impression of Daisy being a more uniform addition,
for example, there is a “gray haze of Daisy’s fur collar” (18), and she is again in a “white” (115) dress
before Tom and Gatsby’s encounter.

San Diego County is very agriculturally productive, thanks to a mild, sunny climate. Common crops include: tomatoes, citrus, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There is a substantial market for organic community supported agriculture food in the San Diego area, with many local organizations having lengthy waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also popular. Many organic farms also provide tours of their agricultural operations as well as access for hiking, birdwatching, and other recreational activities. This is the type of operation that would allow the landowner to gain the benefits of government programs while improving habitat, thus allowing recreational use and creating an opportunity for farm tours and other programs for making money or for educational purposes.  
	In addition to filling a potentially lucrative niche market, the benefits of organic farming often include greater biodiversity in plants and wildlife in the area thanks to a lack of chemicals in the soil and water. However, organic farming has greater costs than conventional farming in some ways. It requires more intensive labor and management to remove pests and weeds and fertilize the soil without chemicals, and losses are often greater than with conventional methods, while a small organic farm also lacks the efficiency of scale of large operations. Practices not related to organic farming but beneficial to wildlife may also incur greater labor costs, including planting cover crops, strategic grazing rotation, invasive species removal, and active management of plant growth to provide specific conditions such as edge habitat or patches of open ground. Thus, there are many reasons why the landowner in this example might seek financial help or expertise in maximizing both profits and habitat quality.  
The land chosen for this scenario is a parcel adjacent to the town of Potrero, in unincorporated San Diego County, California. It is 160 acres of chaparral, nonnative Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland next to to the Cleveland National Forest. It lies in the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan. The plan is still being reviewed, but presently considers over a hundred species of plants and animals. Many are endangered, such as the Stephens' kangaroo rat, the mountain yellow-legged frog, several species of butterfly, and the California gnatcatcher; others are declining and may soon be listed, such as burrowing owls.
	This area was inhabited by Native Americans for untold centuries and was then settled by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 1800's. This piece of land was part of an original homestead patent and so was probably used for grazing and/or wood production for many of the intervening decades.
	 chose a piece of property from a real estate website and researched available government programs to see what options a small farmer might realistically have for mitigating costs and preserving wildlife-friendly operations.  As a model of what somebody farming this land might attempt to achieve, I located an organic farm in the same area.

There is a bond between brothers; an unbreakable, irrevocable bond. Within that bond lie many emotions: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty, just to name a few. Brothers understand one another, far more than anyone else with that kind of bond, and they can only see themselves when looking at their brother. It is when a situation is at its most dire when the true nature of this bond shines through, be it good or evil. When these emotions become clear, they carry with them great a cost. Part of understanding the emotions born of this fraternal link is dealing with the consequences that they bring. When one can look a brother in the eye and see within that person their own reflection, they see themselves not as others see them, but as they truly are. In their actions and the consequences of those actions is where their true character lies.  In “The Scarlet Ibis”, two brothers explore this theme, and all of the raging emotions that accompany it. Throughout a lush, vividly described landscape, these two boys set out on a futile journey. Bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride in the climactic scene, and only one brother escapes with his life. The theme is expressed through direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions with each other, as well as through the narrator’s point of view, which communicates the complex feelings experienced by the protagonist and his view of the world around him, both of which are heavy influences on his actions.
	The protagonist’s actions can all be summed up by one key emotion: pride. From the time he and his little brother, Doodle, first go out together, to their final, fateful excursion, the protagonist feels resentment towards Doodle. He had wanted a brother whom he could teach all of his worldly skills, like “…holding my breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp…” He wanted a brother who could fill the role of “…someone to race to Horsehead Landing…and someone to perch with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn…” Obviously these things are impossible, given Doodle’s condition. Doodle was born with an extremely weak heart, making in unlikely he would even survive. Even then, it was nearly impossible that he would ever participate in vigorous physical activity. What a blow to the young protagonist, his head filled with wild fantasies, to have all of those dreams crushed in an instant. In fact, he is even shown to bear some anger towards the small child, as he recalls beginning to contemplate killing him by suffocating him with a pillow. What kind of child would have the presence of mind to consider infanticide? However, his heart melts when the small child smiles at him. Such a simple act gave the protagonist such hope! This shows that his conviction probably was not very strong. In the back of his mind, he had an instinctive love for his brother.

The human brain is a complicated, creative information-processing system. As technology advanced from primitive to modern, the metaphors used to describe the brain also advanced. Initially, it was compared to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and most recently, to a computer. As you learn about the brain, keep in mind that the usefulness of these metaphors is limited and can lead to erroneous conclusions.
Information processing starts with input from the sensory organs, which transform physical stimuli such as touch, heat, sound waves, or photons of light into electrochemical signals. The sensory information is repeatedly transformed by the algorithms of the brain in both bottom-up and top-down processing. For example, when looking at a picture of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing puts together very simple information such as color, orientation, and where the borders of the object are – where the color changes significantly over a short space – to decide that you are seeing a box. Top-down processing uses the decisions made at some steps of the bottom-up process to speed up your recognition of the box. Top-down processing in this example might help you identify the object as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in the white background.
Once information is processed to a degree, an attention filter decides how important the signal is and which cognitive processes it should be made available to. For example, although your brain processes every blade of grass when you look down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. In contrast, you might pick out your name, even when spoken in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and the results of processing are modulated by attention repeatedly.
In order for the brain to process information, it must first be stored. There are multiple types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term. First, information is encoded. There are types of encoding specific to each type of sensory stimuli. For example, verbal input can be encoded structurally, referring to what the printed word looks like, phonemically, referring to what the word sounds like, or semantically, referring to what the word means. Once information is stored, it must be maintained. Some animal studies suggest that working memory, which stores information for roughly 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through a particular series of neurons for a short period of time. Information in long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained in the structure of certain types of proteins.
There are numerous models of how the knowledge is organized in the brain, some based on the way human subjects retrieve memories, others based on computer science, and others based on neurophysiology. The semantic network model states that there are nodes representing concepts, and that the nodes are linked based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, “chair” might be linked to “table,” which can be linked to “wooden,” and so forth.

In 2007, the United States of America fell into a crushing financial crisis. Unemployment increased, the housing market crashed, and many of America’s largest and most important corportations were left in ruin. This recession persists today, so we must ask the question: how did this crisis occur, and how can we stop it? In short, the financial crisis was created by selfish and naïve political decision-making that pressured banks and firms into issuing sub-prime loans into an already immature and unsufficient financial infrastructure. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to underwite and repackage these mortgages into CDO’s and CDS’. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, the banks were short on capital reserve and transferred this chaos onto the repacked mortgages that they had sold, and on to the rest of the economy.
	The financial crisis had its roots in 1999 of the Clinton era, as the President was aiming for a second term in office. He sought to extend his presidential tenure by augmenting his popularity. To accomplish this the Clinton administration relaxed lending restrictions, which helped to set the grim stage for the sub-prime crisis seven years later.  Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported in 1999, “Fannie Mae, the nation's biggest underwriter of home mortgages, has been under increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans among low and moderate income people and felt pressure from stock holders to maintain its phenomenal growth in profits.” Holmes would go on to correctly foresee the consequences of these actions: “But the government-subsidized corporation may run into trouble in an economic downturn, prompting a government rescue similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.” As detailed in the introduction, and as Holmes foresaw, ill-advised lending would certainly lead to the meltdown of the economy.
	Many factors combined to throw the economy into tailspin, one of which was the new and complex structure of mortgages. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDO’s) were all used extensively in the years leading up to the crisis, and only served to intertwine more sectors of the economy into the housing market. This led to U.S. households, and financial markets in general, to overleverage themselves in the housing market, leaving them extremely vulnerable to even small changes in price. 
	Indeed, the housing bubble burst, and the financial institutions that had bought these mortgage-backed securities were spited. The top five U.S. investment banks all together reported $4.1 trillion dollars of mortgage debts in 2007, which accounted for about 30% of the USA’s GDP. In the end, Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold exceptionally cheap, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks subjected to intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie were $5 trillion in mortgage debt, and were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition.  That place in your story where you stretch your little writer's wings and take flight, astounding one and all with your magnetic, nay magical prose.  Or the part where your readers fall asleep and/or hit the "Back" button while cursing your name.  Dr. Merlin has been known to shout at her monitor when she finds herself in the middle of Too Much Information, and not even in the fun way.

Exposition is not your friend.

My gentle readers already know the basic writing tip, "Show, don't tell," but Dr. Merlin still stumbles into long passages of text where nothing happens, or worse, too much.  Exposition is the little devil sitting on your shoulder that says to get the history out of the way to get to the good parts (not to be confused with the devil sitting on the other shoulder urging the author to tell her audience every single detail of the childhoods of each character).

Exposition means telling the audience what happened, typically in simple prose.  In film, the exposition happens when one character tells another a core-dump of information ala "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner."  In fiction, the author's doing the telling.

An example is in order.  As you are reading a story, you are told that the heroine met her beloved at such a place and time, that they were married in a gala fashion, and that her husband was murdered in front of her eyes.  You would not expect this entire sequence to take two pages, during which time both he and she only get two lines of dialogue each.  You would expect the author to spend some time on the husband's character, evidencing by his speech and manner how deeply he loves his wife, and you would equally expect the heroine to show through big and small ways how much his presence in her life changed and enriched her (especially if the story were to tell you flat out later that this was the case).  A proper introduction to the husband's character would allow you to become emotionally involved with his fate and would give you insight into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, how deep their bond was, clues about her thoughts and beliefs and dreams as reflected through the prism of his eyes, and so on.  You would mourn his death with her, and so grow more connected to the heroine herself.

In short, you would expect meat on the simple bone of the storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to provide that meat.  (*looks at metaphor, sighs, plunges onward*)  Sometimes it is tempting to rush past certain things.  Perhaps you're introducing a new character and you know he used to be in the Air Force, and he's the night manager of a gas station now, and he was married twice, no kids, likes to go fishing on the weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station someday and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I watched two newscast’s from Columbus, Ohio. The first one that was “live” was NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). I think they spent an appropriate amount of time on this story. 
	The second story was about an early morning shooting of Travis Buyers, 18. He was shot in the Sharon Woods area and had been critically injured; there had been no arrests made at the time or any suspects. The SWAT Team was investigating the crime. 	The next story was concerning the rain and thunderstorms predicted for Saturday afternoon. They said the temperatures would remain in the mid to low eighties for the weekend. The length of time was a little short, but they wanted to use it as a “teaser” so that you would stay tuned. 
	They also ran with a story about a robbery of a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. They said it was dark-skinned black man who robbed the store he was wearing a hoodie sweatshirt. They said he was about six-foot tall and weighed about one hundred and fifty pounds. I thought they devoted an unusual about of time emphasizing he was black and how dark he was.
